00:01:41.630 --> 00:01:44.440
- I do study chimpanzees in a savanna

00:01:44.440 --> 00:01:45.273
and I'd like to tell you

00:01:45.273 --> 00:01:46.660
a little bit more about that site

00:01:46.660 --> 00:01:48.480
because it does have a lot of

00:01:48.480 --> 00:01:51.820
importance as far as the
chimpanzees' hunting behavior goes.

00:01:51.820 --> 00:01:53.700
And this map I will show you,

00:01:53.700 --> 00:01:57.210
most of the long-term
chimpanzee study sites

00:01:57.210 --> 00:01:58.790
operating today, not all of them,

00:01:58.790 --> 00:02:02.910
but these sites most
of them here have been

00:02:02.910 --> 00:02:04.530
ongoing for at least 10 years

00:02:04.530 --> 00:02:07.810
and in some cases and the
case of Gombe and Mahale

00:02:07.810 --> 00:02:09.060
more than 50 years.

00:02:09.060 --> 00:02:12.090
And so, most of you are probably
familiar with Jane Goodall

00:02:12.090 --> 00:02:14.610
and at least the person,

00:02:14.610 --> 00:02:18.170
but Gombe is the site that
she helped to establish

00:02:18.170 --> 00:02:19.440
that Ian talked about.

00:02:19.440 --> 00:02:22.060
I'm across the continent

00:02:22.060 --> 00:02:23.730
and I'm over in West Africa,

00:02:23.730 --> 00:02:27.250
this is my site, the Fongoli study site.

00:02:27.250 --> 00:02:30.600
And I chose this site
because it is in a savanna

00:02:30.600 --> 00:02:33.143
and we think that our lineage,

00:02:34.140 --> 00:02:38.520
evolutionarily speaking
evolved in this type of habitat

00:02:38.520 --> 00:02:41.594
and so, I'll show you
some images from the site.

00:02:41.594 --> 00:02:45.280
My underlying questions have to do with

00:02:45.280 --> 00:02:46.780
how these chimpanzees differ

00:02:46.780 --> 00:02:48.520
from chimpanzees living in forests,

00:02:48.520 --> 00:02:50.100
like the chimps we've heard about before

00:02:50.100 --> 00:02:51.880
and in Goualougo and in Gombe.

00:02:51.880 --> 00:02:54.950
And I will cite Jim Moore here,

00:02:54.950 --> 00:02:56.890
he's written a lot about using chimpanzees

00:02:56.890 --> 00:02:58.550
as what we call a referential model

00:02:58.550 --> 00:03:01.210
and that is comparing them to

00:03:01.210 --> 00:03:02.707
chimpanzees living in a forested site.

00:03:02.707 --> 00:03:05.660
And the assumption is that
the environment will have

00:03:05.660 --> 00:03:07.100
effects on their behavior.

00:03:07.100 --> 00:03:08.760
And I did think this going in,

00:03:08.760 --> 00:03:11.060
I had ideas about what
the differences might be

00:03:11.060 --> 00:03:13.160
and the chimps kind of went their own way

00:03:13.160 --> 00:03:16.100
and showed me a lot more
differences including hunting,

00:03:16.100 --> 00:03:18.223
and so I'll talk to you about that today.

00:03:19.990 --> 00:03:22.810
So though I'm going to talk
about three main questions

00:03:22.810 --> 00:03:26.030
and I focus on the types of hunting

00:03:26.030 --> 00:03:28.660
or aspects of the Fongoli
chimpanzees' hunting

00:03:28.660 --> 00:03:31.450
that you don't necessarily
see at other sites

00:03:31.450 --> 00:03:33.083
or that are very rare.

00:03:34.420 --> 00:03:37.230
And so one of the things
that we see here commonly

00:03:37.230 --> 00:03:38.423
is that chimpanzees hunt with tools

00:03:38.423 --> 00:03:42.060
and that's something that we
use to define our own species.

00:03:42.060 --> 00:03:45.070
It has been seen literally
a handful of times

00:03:45.070 --> 00:03:47.030
at another site in Tanzania

00:03:47.030 --> 00:03:51.020
but at Fongoli chimpanzees
do this quite frequently

00:03:51.020 --> 00:03:52.780
so we've seen hundreds of cases now

00:03:52.780 --> 00:03:55.480
and I'll talk to you more about that.

00:03:55.480 --> 00:03:58.140
So one of the questions that I'll touch on

00:03:58.140 --> 00:04:01.573
is why hunt with tools in
this particular habitat?

00:04:02.670 --> 00:04:04.720
Something else that is not really common

00:04:04.720 --> 00:04:07.640
at other chimpanzee
sites is that in fact in

00:04:07.640 --> 00:04:10.050
regarding this particular type of hunting,

00:04:10.050 --> 00:04:13.310
females are more frequently going to be

00:04:13.310 --> 00:04:15.500
those hunting with
tools compared to males,

00:04:15.500 --> 00:04:17.890
and as we heard that's just not the case

00:04:17.890 --> 00:04:19.710
in most other chimpanzee study sites

00:04:19.710 --> 00:04:21.563
so I'll talk more about that.

00:04:22.780 --> 00:04:26.160
And then to follow up with David's talk

00:04:26.160 --> 00:04:27.960
I will talk about meat sharing

00:04:27.960 --> 00:04:29.100
or I use the word sharing

00:04:29.100 --> 00:04:31.500
and I'll talk about how I define that,

00:04:31.500 --> 00:04:35.263
but I'll specifically talk
about how females dole out meat.

00:04:37.290 --> 00:04:40.890
And then finally I'll come
back to this idea about

00:04:40.890 --> 00:04:42.490
using chimpanzees as a model

00:04:42.490 --> 00:04:45.470
and what perhaps the Fongoli
chimpanzees that I study

00:04:45.470 --> 00:04:49.510
can help us say or think about in terms of

00:04:49.510 --> 00:04:53.663
the evolution of early hominin
or bipedal ape hunting.

00:04:57.190 --> 00:04:59.600
So these are some images
from my study site,

00:04:59.600 --> 00:05:02.530
the Fongoli study site
is one of the hottest,

00:05:02.530 --> 00:05:07.530
driest and most vegetatively
open sites that you see today

00:05:07.810 --> 00:05:10.270
where chimpanzees have
actually been habituated

00:05:10.270 --> 00:05:11.670
to a human presence.

00:05:11.670 --> 00:05:13.230
So this took us quite a long time,

00:05:13.230 --> 00:05:14.300
it took us four years.

00:05:14.300 --> 00:05:19.080
I started in 2001 and we
habituated males to our presence

00:05:19.080 --> 00:05:22.160
by 2005 but I wasn't able to identify

00:05:22.160 --> 00:05:25.240
all the chimpanzees in
the group until 2006.

00:05:25.240 --> 00:05:27.660
That's when we identified all the females,

00:05:27.660 --> 00:05:31.100
this is a view of my
pretty fancy camp there.

00:05:31.100 --> 00:05:34.300
And hopefully that gives you
some idea of the vegetation.

00:05:34.300 --> 00:05:36.020
So it's a woodland savanna,

00:05:36.020 --> 00:05:39.430
the dominant understory
is grass the savanna

00:05:39.430 --> 00:05:42.260
but you do have a large proportion

00:05:42.260 --> 00:05:43.760
of the habitat as woodlands.

00:05:43.760 --> 00:05:45.850
Over half of the habitat is woodland

00:05:45.850 --> 00:05:49.130
and only a very small portion is forest,

00:05:49.130 --> 00:05:51.210
about 3% of the habitat is forest

00:05:51.210 --> 00:05:53.400
and this is where you
find your water sources.

00:05:53.400 --> 00:05:56.220
This is really the chimpanzees'
most limiting resource

00:05:56.220 --> 00:05:57.700
at Fongoli is water.

00:05:57.700 --> 00:05:59.540
Temperatures are incredibly hot,

00:05:59.540 --> 00:06:01.890
really hot for me, even hot for chimps.

00:06:01.890 --> 00:06:04.940
So right now we're, well,

00:06:04.940 --> 00:06:07.700
yeah, the month of March in Senegal is

00:06:07.700 --> 00:06:09.670
almost approaching the
peak of the dry season

00:06:09.670 --> 00:06:13.160
so temperatures are regularly
over a hundred degrees.

00:06:13.160 --> 00:06:16.440
They may get up to 115 or so.

00:06:16.440 --> 00:06:17.710
During the rainy season

00:06:17.710 --> 00:06:19.320
or at least at the beginning
of the rainy season

00:06:19.320 --> 00:06:20.250
you find some relief

00:06:20.250 --> 00:06:22.180
because the trees will
put out leaves again.

00:06:22.180 --> 00:06:24.660
They lose all their trees
during the dry season.

00:06:24.660 --> 00:06:27.070
But yet you have this lag,
you have hot temperatures

00:06:27.070 --> 00:06:29.540
and then you have this high
humidity which is really fun.

00:06:29.540 --> 00:06:34.540
And so, literally the heat
index in June is around 120, 125

00:06:36.600 --> 00:06:38.729
and that's when I take students out.

00:06:38.729 --> 00:06:42.350
(audience laughing)

00:06:42.350 --> 00:06:44.683
So a little bit about
the Fongoli study group.

00:06:45.810 --> 00:06:47.250
Within this particular habitat

00:06:47.250 --> 00:06:50.410
they have a very large
home range, 110 kilometers,

00:06:50.410 --> 00:06:51.600
which is one of the largest

00:06:51.600 --> 00:06:54.920
if not the largest so far described.

00:06:54.920 --> 00:06:56.920
The community size is relatively small,

00:06:56.920 --> 00:06:59.380
it's not the smallest
chimpanzee community studied

00:06:59.380 --> 00:07:02.040
but it's on the small
size, around 35 chimps.

00:07:02.040 --> 00:07:04.770
And importantly we have
a sex ratio that is

00:07:04.770 --> 00:07:07.760
sort of the opposite of
what you see at other sites.

00:07:07.760 --> 00:07:09.310
So we have more males than females,

00:07:09.310 --> 00:07:11.510
that's usually not the case.

00:07:11.510 --> 00:07:14.900
And the data that I'm
gonna talk about today

00:07:14.900 --> 00:07:18.533
stem from 2005 through 2017.

00:07:19.440 --> 00:07:22.720
One other thing I'll say about adult males

00:07:22.720 --> 00:07:24.600
versus adult females is

00:07:24.600 --> 00:07:26.913
because of the fact that
when I first got to Fongoli

00:07:26.913 --> 00:07:28.490
I heard that even though chimpanzees

00:07:28.490 --> 00:07:30.190
are not eaten at the site

00:07:30.190 --> 00:07:31.840
and this is not within a national park,

00:07:31.840 --> 00:07:33.320
this is outside of a national park

00:07:33.320 --> 00:07:35.730
so you do have villages in the area.

00:07:35.730 --> 00:07:38.060
Anthropogenic or human
disturbance accounts

00:07:38.060 --> 00:07:40.120
for about 5% of the habitat.

00:07:40.120 --> 00:07:42.580
You do have chimpanzees
living alongside people,

00:07:42.580 --> 00:07:43.800
they're not habituated to them,

00:07:43.800 --> 00:07:45.640
they're habituated to us so we're okay

00:07:45.640 --> 00:07:47.180
but other people are not.

00:07:47.180 --> 00:07:48.930
But in rare cases you do have people

00:07:48.930 --> 00:07:50.440
that will try to hunt a chimpanzee

00:07:50.440 --> 00:07:53.100
in order to get a female's
infant for the pet trade

00:07:53.100 --> 00:07:56.120
and we had that happen
one time in 17 years.

00:07:56.120 --> 00:07:58.620
And because of that I focus on adult males

00:07:58.620 --> 00:08:00.410
as my focal subjects.

00:08:00.410 --> 00:08:03.130
The Fongoli community is often
together as one large group

00:08:03.130 --> 00:08:05.470
so I can collect data on females,

00:08:05.470 --> 00:08:08.010
but they are more timid
when they're by themselves

00:08:08.010 --> 00:08:10.980
and I don't try to follow them
when they're by themselves.

00:08:10.980 --> 00:08:14.310
So I think I know a lot about
what is going on with males

00:08:14.310 --> 00:08:16.680
and I know some about what
is going on with females

00:08:16.680 --> 00:08:18.223
but perhaps not as much.

00:08:20.370 --> 00:08:22.940
So this pie chart gives you an idea

00:08:22.940 --> 00:08:25.970
of the prey species consumed
by Fongoli chimpanzees

00:08:25.970 --> 00:08:28.420
both by males and by females.

00:08:28.420 --> 00:08:31.220
And as Ian pointed out

00:08:31.220 --> 00:08:33.940
there are no colobus monkeys
in this particular habitat.

00:08:33.940 --> 00:08:35.900
So it is a savanna woodland habitat,

00:08:35.900 --> 00:08:38.140
colobus monkeys don't occur here.

00:08:38.140 --> 00:08:39.950
Forest guenons like red-tailed monkeys

00:08:39.950 --> 00:08:42.840
or other colobus monkeys, blue
monkeys do not occur here.

00:08:42.840 --> 00:08:45.750
Instead you have savanna
species like baboons,

00:08:45.750 --> 00:08:48.073
patas monkeys, vervets.

00:08:49.076 --> 00:08:51.530
You have mongooses,
bushbucks, things like this.

00:08:51.530 --> 00:08:52.870
And then on the very lower right

00:08:52.870 --> 00:08:54.810
you see that adorable little bush baby

00:08:54.810 --> 00:08:57.560
and Ian introduced the galago as well.

00:08:57.560 --> 00:09:00.620
The galago is actually
the main prey species

00:09:00.620 --> 00:09:04.030
of Fongoli chimpanzees,
both males and females,

00:09:04.030 --> 00:09:06.830
and this is the animal
that they hunt with tools

00:09:06.830 --> 00:09:09.080
and I'll actually hopefully
show you some video of that

00:09:09.080 --> 00:09:11.530
and talk more about that.

00:09:11.530 --> 00:09:14.330
So the prey profile if
you wanna call it that

00:09:14.330 --> 00:09:17.590
really reflects the
savanna type of habitat

00:09:17.590 --> 00:09:21.090
and it does also support
as Ian pointed out

00:09:21.930 --> 00:09:24.713
or talked about what is
called a risk-averse strategy.

00:09:25.850 --> 00:09:27.360
So I'm just going to show you some video

00:09:27.360 --> 00:09:29.643
and try to narrate it here.

00:09:31.860 --> 00:09:34.280
So this is tool-assisted hunting.

00:09:34.280 --> 00:09:35.550
What this image is gonna show you

00:09:35.550 --> 00:09:38.040
is an adult female
that's if you can't tell,

00:09:38.040 --> 00:09:40.050
that's Farafa, she's an older female.

00:09:40.050 --> 00:09:42.080
We estimate her age to be around 40.

00:09:42.080 --> 00:09:45.193
She's one of the top female
hunters in the group.

00:09:46.300 --> 00:09:49.330
So she's trying to get at these
adorable little bush babies

00:09:49.330 --> 00:09:51.450
that try to sleep in
cavities during the day

00:09:51.450 --> 00:09:54.170
until this rude chimpanzee
comes with the tool.

00:09:54.170 --> 00:09:56.990
That's an adult male, that's Jumpkin

00:09:56.990 --> 00:09:59.453
and he goes about it a
little bit differently.

00:10:02.199 --> 00:10:05.199
(audience laughing)

00:10:07.620 --> 00:10:10.390
And so, even though
females hunt with tools

00:10:10.390 --> 00:10:12.090
more than expected,

00:10:12.090 --> 00:10:14.410
I'll talk a little bit
more about that next,

00:10:14.410 --> 00:10:17.392
males do exhibit this type
of hunting behavior as well.

00:10:17.392 --> 00:10:20.270
(audience laughing)

00:10:20.270 --> 00:10:22.123
I have to say he's
usually better than that.

00:10:22.123 --> 00:10:23.420
(audience laughing)

00:10:23.420 --> 00:10:25.123
They just caught him on a bad day.

00:10:27.493 --> 00:10:30.493
(audience laughing)

00:10:40.192 --> 00:10:43.692
Well, we'll let Jumpkin try one more time.

00:10:46.065 --> 00:10:49.065
(audience laughing)

00:10:53.660 --> 00:10:56.600
If you didn't guess he wasn't successful

00:10:56.600 --> 00:10:58.590
in this particular bout.

00:10:58.590 --> 00:11:00.983
So we're looking at a lot of
different aspects of this.

00:11:00.983 --> 00:11:01.816
Well.

00:11:01.816 --> 00:11:03.780
(audience laughing)

00:11:03.780 --> 00:11:05.343
I almost feel bad showing that.

00:11:06.680 --> 00:11:08.110
We're looking at a lot
of different aspects

00:11:08.110 --> 00:11:09.790
of this particular behavior

00:11:09.790 --> 00:11:13.130
and so this is a juvenile female, Vivian,

00:11:13.130 --> 00:11:14.830
that was her mother that was hunting.

00:11:14.830 --> 00:11:18.090
And the juveniles start this behavior

00:11:18.090 --> 00:11:19.500
when they're about two years of age,

00:11:19.500 --> 00:11:21.640
when they're still infants and nursing

00:11:21.640 --> 00:11:24.050
but they don't learn really the proper

00:11:25.410 --> 00:11:26.830
tool length and that sort of thing

00:11:26.830 --> 00:11:28.910
until they get to be about four.

00:11:28.910 --> 00:11:30.876
So she gets a little frustrated too.

00:11:30.876 --> 00:11:33.120
(audience laughing)

00:11:33.120 --> 00:11:35.363
All right, enough fun I guess.

00:11:36.650 --> 00:11:40.610
So in terms of our results so far,

00:11:40.610 --> 00:11:43.550
I apologize because in your
abstract I put over 500,

00:11:43.550 --> 00:11:47.250
I was sure that we would
hit the 500 mark this year.

00:11:47.250 --> 00:11:49.525
499, I just can't believe it.

00:11:49.525 --> 00:11:50.500
(audience laughs)

00:11:50.500 --> 00:11:52.680
But we have 499 hunting records,

00:11:52.680 --> 00:11:54.380
those aren't all successes

00:11:54.380 --> 00:11:56.680
and that's including adults and immatures.

00:11:56.680 --> 00:11:59.180
We've only seen adolescent
and adult individuals

00:11:59.180 --> 00:12:01.890
successful in this type
of hunting behavior.

00:12:01.890 --> 00:12:03.900
Like I said infants begin to exhibit it

00:12:03.900 --> 00:12:05.720
and they do really good
as far as making the tool

00:12:05.720 --> 00:12:07.500
but they don't make a proper tool

00:12:07.500 --> 00:12:09.800
until they get to be a juvenile.

00:12:09.800 --> 00:12:13.020
So we see about 32 hunts
per year on average

00:12:13.020 --> 00:12:14.960
when you take into account
that there are some days

00:12:14.960 --> 00:12:16.470
that we can't be there,
the river's too high

00:12:16.470 --> 00:12:17.930
or someone's sick.

00:12:17.930 --> 00:12:21.650
We think that they probably
hunt at least 50 times a year.

00:12:21.650 --> 00:12:24.640
And again, our most recent
analysis suggest that

00:12:24.640 --> 00:12:27.920
females do hunt significantly
more than expected with tools

00:12:28.790 --> 00:12:30.050
even though males also hunt.

00:12:30.050 --> 00:12:33.450
And we did analysis taking into account

00:12:33.450 --> 00:12:36.580
not only their membership in
the the community as a whole

00:12:36.580 --> 00:12:37.580
but also their membership

00:12:37.580 --> 00:12:39.600
and so-called hunting parties

00:12:39.600 --> 00:12:42.593
or parties that the chimpanzees
are in on those days.

00:12:43.930 --> 00:12:45.940
So I want to talk a little bit more about

00:12:45.940 --> 00:12:48.660
just the hunters themselves

00:12:48.660 --> 00:12:50.610
and this is a lot of color there

00:12:50.610 --> 00:12:54.340
but I wanted to show you the
top 10 hunters at Fongoli

00:12:54.340 --> 00:12:56.510
and also the different types of foods

00:12:56.510 --> 00:12:58.460
or prey that they hunt.

00:12:58.460 --> 00:13:01.970
And so, you have two
females that are actually

00:13:01.970 --> 00:13:04.380
among the top 10 hunters at Fongoli.

00:13:04.380 --> 00:13:07.220
Interestingly I think is
that both of those females,

00:13:07.220 --> 00:13:08.860
females are very high-ranking.

00:13:08.860 --> 00:13:11.500
So Tumbo there is
currently our alpha female

